description:
Implement algorithm to detect separate workstreams within a label by analyzing graph connectivity.

## Problem
When a user selects a generic label like `infra`, they may get unrelated issues:
- BV-09 Redis queue (part of inbound-emails feature)
- BV-31 Migration runner (part of devops epic)
- BV-22 Logging setup (standalone)

These should be grouped into separate "workstreams" for clarity.

## Algorithm
Two issues belong to the same workstream if they're connected through the dependency graph (directly or transitively).

```go
func detectWorkstreams(issues []Issue) []Workstream {
    // Build adjacency list (bidirectional - both deps and dependents)
    graph := buildBidirectionalGraph(issues)

    // Find connected components using BFS/DFS
    visited := map[string]bool{}
    workstreams := []Workstream{}

    for _, issue := range issues {
        if !visited[issue.ID] {
            component := bfsComponent(issue.ID, graph, visited)
            workstreams = append(workstreams, Workstream{
                Issues: component,
            })
        }
    }

    return workstreams
}
```

## Data Structures
```go
type Workstream struct {
    Name        string    // auto-detected or "standalone"
    Issues      []Issue   // all issues in this component
    PrimaryCount int      // issues with the selected label
    ContextCount int      // issues pulled in via deps
    Progress    float64   // closed / total
    IsBlocked   bool      // all actionable issues blocked?
}
```

## Implementation Notes
- Reuse graph structures from `pkg/analysis/`
- Consider edge direction: treat deps as bidirectional for connectivity
- Handle the case where label captures only context issues (indirect workstream)

## Files to modify
- `pkg/analysis/workstream.go` (new)
- `pkg/ui/labeldashboard.go` (use workstream detection)

